Compilation avoidance If a dependent project has changed in an ABI-compatible way (only its private API has changed), then Java compilation tasks will be up-to-date. This means that if project A depends on project B and a class in B is changed in an ABI-compatible way (typically, changing only the body of a method), then Gradle won’t recompile A. Some of the types of changes that do not affect the public API and are ignored: Changing a method body Changing a comment Adding, removing or changing private methods, fields, or inner classes Adding, removing or changing a resource Changing the name of jars or directories in the classpath Renaming a parameter Since implementation details matter for annotation processors, they must be declared separately on the annotation processor path. Gradle ignores annotation processors on the compile classpath. Example 7. Declaring annotation processors
